e matches, you probably won't find them here. However. You can turn off most animations and transitions in this game to speed up the process. And the game saves automatically when you exit it, so you can stop and continue from whatever moment you want. So in all honesty, it's not a big deal. But if you are a kind of person that just MUST see the match from start to finish in one sitting, be aware that it can take 30 minutes or more (depending on how familiar you are with cards and UI).\n\n\tFinally. The thing that actually bothers me most. [b]Multiplayer and DLC[/b].\nThere are a lot of DLC and they are somewhat pricey, which is like... mostly ok. Many games do this. Whatever. Right?\nExcept in this game everybody in your multiplayer match MUST have the same DLC in order for any of you to use it.\nLet me break it down. You can not use DLC you bought in a match with your friend if he does not have it. You still can play together, but the game will disable any DLC the other player does not have. Which is just ridiculous if you ask me. Why do I have to pester my friends to buy the exact same DLC that I own, just so I can play the characters I bought? Or, to put it differently, why can I not play the characters I bought if I want to play with my friends? That's one of the stupidest models I've seen in a while, to be honest, and I just can't get over it.\n\nThis issue may or may not be resolved in the future, since the developers stated that that is not the priority. Right now though things are what they are.\n\nThankfully, this game is still a lot of fun in single player, and the aforementioned DLC bring a lot of content - villains, environments, heroes with their unique decks... but if multiplayer is what you're primarily after, think twice before buying this game. \n\nOtherwise, it is an astonishing game and I can not recommend it enough.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1499708925, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 150091023