ninteresting way to make a quasi-deck-builder. The art and appearance of all this is an amateur comic, with generic feeling heroes and villains fighting in trope-filled environments. Not terrible but not at all impressive. The interface and presentation is also clunky and unremarkable. \n\nNonetheless, because the core game comes with a small number of base decks--heroes, villains, environments--combined with the inability to customize those decks or the game play beyond meta-level selections, the game quickly feels repetitive and monotonous. (Unless you're willing to spend more money to buy diversity, of course!)\n\nLuck also has a notable factor, meaning that a bad string of draws by the villain or environment can cause you to lose the game regardless of how strong you'd played to that point. Like it or not, you're going to lose a portion of games for no other reason than being unlucky. Given the sluggish pace of the game, this can be annoying. \n\nThat said, there is some strategy in what heroes you choose to bring against what villains, which is great. However, as you might surmise, this means that there are more or less optimal choices to bring against a villain or environment, further narrowing the variety and flavor of the game. (Unless you spend more!)\n\nWhile I've dogged it here, I won't say it's a terrible game, but it is slow-paced, occasionally frustrating, and miserly. I would not recommend it over competing card-based games like Obsidian's Pathfinder Adventures, The Elder Scrolls: Legends or Card Hunter, all of which offer more robust and engaging games for more competitive cost. \n\nThe other reason to pick up this game is if you're a fan of the original physical game and can't help yourself.", "received_for_free": false, "timestamp_created": 1499869648, "written_during_early_access": false, "timestamp_updated": 1499869648, "recommendationid": "33480863", "language": "english", "votes_down": 16, "steam_purchase": true, "weighted_vote_score": "0.48130